  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a lived reality for many who've seen their potential dimmed by the very labels society assigns. Growing up in Kansas City, I remember watching my father, a man who earned a bachelor's degree but never worked in a field he loved, struggle with the idea that his 'less than' in math might limit his children's futures. That's when I first grasped how deeply stereotypes can haunt even those who've worked hard. Now, as a retired man who's spent decades volunteering and gardening, I've seen firsthand how the fear of confirming negative stereotypes can make brilliant minds hesitate to engage with STEM fields. It's not about fixing people—it's about changing the environment so that when someone says 'I'm not good at math,' they're not thinking of a lifelong label but of a problem that can be solved together. We should address it by creating classrooms and workplaces where everyone feels safe to make mistakes without judgment. That means teachers who ask, 'What's your thought?' instead of 'Do you know this?' and mentors who share their own struggles with uncertainty. For me, it's about building bridges, not walls. In a world where creativity matters more than ever, we must ensure that the next generation doesn't have to choose between their passion and the fear of being labeled. After all, the best innovations come from people who feel free to explore, not from those who've been told they don't belong.",
